            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Harris was born and raised in the Richmond District of San Francisco, the middle child in a working-class family. His father, a longshoreman, and his mother, a bookkeeper, instilled in him a strong sense of responsibility and a deep appreciation for their city. School was a pragmatic affair for David; after graduating George Washington High School with a focus on general studies, college wasn't a financial possibility.\n\nHis early adulthood was a series of blue-collar jobs \u2013 delivery driver, warehouse worker \u2013 each a stepping stone but never a destination. The turning point came in his late twenties when a friend suggested he apply for the Parking Enforcement Officer position. It wasn\u2019t glamorous, but it offered stability, decent benefits, and a chance to be truly out and about in the city he loved. The civil service exam felt daunting, but he buckled down, passed, and found his niche.\n\nOver the past two decades, David has become a familiar figure on the streets, particularly around the Marina and North Beach where he\u2019s often assigned. He\u2019s developed a thick skin, learning to navigate the frustrations of the public with a blend of firmness and unexpected moments of dry wit. His colleagues are his second family; they understand the unique challenges of the job and offer a crucial support system.\n\nDavid has been married twice, both marriages ending amicably, leaving him with a pragmatic view of relationships. He has a daughter, Emily, in her early twenties, who is pursuing a degree in nursing down in San Diego. Their phone calls and occasional visits are highlights of his week.\n\nHis current life is one of routine. Up early to ride his well-maintained motorcycle to work, spending his days enforcing parking regulations, and often unwinding in the evenings with classic movies or tinkering in his small garage. He enjoys the simple pleasures: a good slice of pizza in North Beach, the view from the Golden Gate Bridge during his commute, and the feeling of knowing the city\u2019s pulse.\n\nDavid\u2019s hopes are modest. He dreams of a quiet retirement, perhaps somewhere less expensive than San Francisco but close enough for Emily to visit easily. He\u2019d like to travel a bit, maybe see some more of California. Mostly, though, he hopes for continued health and the ability to continue his work, contributing in his own way to the order of his beloved, chaotic city. He feels a deep connection to San Francisco; it\u2019s in his blood, the backdrop to his entire life, and he can\u2019t imagine being anywhere else."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The smell of salty air and the rough feel of his father\u2019s calloused hand guiding his small one along the Embarcadero docks. David remembered the rhythmic clang of cargo being loaded and unloaded, a symphony of the working waterfront.  It cemented a feeling of belonging, of his family being intrinsically part of this city's engine, fueling his lifelong connection to San Francisco. This memory is from his childhood.\n\n2. Sitting on a park bench near Washington Square, sharing a greasy slice of Tony\u2019s pizza with a seasoned Parking Enforcement colleague. They talked about frustrating drivers and the fleeting glimpses of beauty they saw every day. This conversation, early in his career, made David realize this job, while tough, also offered comradeship and unexpected moments of shared humanity.  It happened in his late twenties.\n\n3. Holding Emily\u2019s tiny hand as they walked across the Golden Gate Bridge on a rare sunny day. The vast expanse of the bay below mirrored the vastness of his love and hopes for her future. This moment, years ago when Emily was a child, solidified his purpose \u2013 working hard to provide for her, even in a city that demanded so much.\n\n4.  Getting a heartfelt thank you from an elderly woman in the Marina after helping her navigate a tricky parking situation.  It was just a few kind words, a small gesture, but it cut through the daily grind of complaints and reminded him of the quiet positive impact his work could have. It happened recently, in his mid-forties.\n\n5. The quiet satisfaction of starting his motorcycle early in the morning, the engine purring as he rode through the near-empty Richmond streets, the city slowly waking up around him. This simple ritual, a daily occurrence for two decades, represented freedom, independence, and the enduring satisfaction of starting his day in the heart of his beloved San Francisco."
